			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It's also not <em>no</em> graphics. You can still do blocky sprites. You can still do raster effects. (Which raster effects you can can fit in will be limited due to paucity of RAM).<br /><br />In practice, I've noticed that floating pins on the NES cart connector (meaning specifically NTRAM/CE and NTRAMA10) very loosely capacitively couple with whatever's around, which in practice means &quot;coupling with mains frequency&quot;. So a small portion of the screen will actually get valid data from RAM... See <a href="https://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=95339#p95339" class="postlink">ccovell's Theremin</a>.<br /><br /><br />(The blocky sprite tiles that you do get, when NTRAM/CE is floating high, will look like:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">wxyz2ttt<br />wxyz2tt3<br />wxyz2t3t<br />wxyz2t33<br />wxyz23tt<br />wxyz23t3<br />wxyz233t<br />wxyz2333</div>where &quot;t&quot;=transparent, &quot;2&quot; and &quot;3&quot;=palette entries 2 and 3, and &quot;wxyz&quot; = the lower 4 bits of the sprite #, in binary, where set bits are color 3 and clear bits are transparent.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

